
```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>   
using namespace std;

// Class Definition
class Teacher {

private:
    // Private Data Member
    // Cannot be accessed directly outside the class
    double salary;

public:
    // Public Data Members
    string name;
    string dept;
    string subject;

    // Member Function
    // Used to change department
    void changeDept(string newdept) {
        dept = newdept;
    }

    // Setter Function
    // Used to modify private variable
    void setSalary(double s) {
        salary = s;
    }

    // Getter Function
    // Used to access private variable
    double getSalary() {
        return salary;
    }
};

// Main Function
// Program execution starts here
int main() {

    // Object Creation
    // t1 is an object of class Teacher
    Teacher t1;

    // Accessing Public Data Members using dot operator
    t1.name = "Mukunda Sai";
    t1.dept = "Computer Science";
    t1.subject = "C++";

    // Calling Member Function
    cout << t1.name << endl;

    // Calling Setter Function
    t1.setSalary(2000);

    // Calling Getter Function
    cout << t1.getSalary() << endl;

    return 0;
}
```

---------------------------------------------------------------------

Concepts Explained

Class  
A class is a blueprint used to create objects.

Object  
An object is an instance of a class.  
Example: Teacher t1;

Access Specifiers  

private  
Members accessible only inside the class.

public  
Members accessible anywhere in the program.

Encapsulation  
The salary variable is private.  
It can only be accessed using getter and setter functions.  
This protects data from direct modification.

Dot Operator  
Used to access data members and member functions.  
Example: t1.name  
Example: t1.setSalary()

